gland"},"en":{"1322–1395":"1322–1395","1320–1390":"1320–1390","1350–1401":"1350–1401","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1401":"1401","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1390":"about 1390","1390":"1390","1328":"1328","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Chilwell, Broxtowe district, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chilwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Chilwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Chilwell, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Culting","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the personal name <b>Cutt</b> (a pet form of <i>Cudbert</i>, see   Cuthbert  ) + the suffix <i>-ing</i>.","Americanized form of German <b>Kötting</b> or the variant <b>Kotting</b> (see   Koetting  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Cuthbert","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Cudbert</i>, Old English <i>Cuthbeorht</i>, composed of the elements <i>cūth</i> ‘famous, well known’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, bishop of Hexham and later of Lindisfarne, and remained popular because of his cult throughout the Middle Ages, especially in northern England and the lowlands of Scotland.","Scottish: variant of <b>Coubrough</b>, an Anglicized and shortened form of   McCoubrey  , from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac Cuithbreith</b> ‘son of Cuthbert’ (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Gutting","meanings":["German (also <b>Gütting</b>): probably from an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’.","Perhaps an altered form of English   Cutting  ."]}]},{"name":"Basile","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Basileios</i> ‘royal’ (a derivative of <i>basileus</i> ‘king’). This name was borne by  St Basil  the Great (  <i>c.</i>330–379 ), bishop of Caesarea, a theologian regarded as one of the Fathers of the Eastern Church. It was also the name of several early saints martyred in the East."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eve","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["vernacular form of the name borne in the Bible by the first woman, created from one of Adam's ribs (Genesis 2:22). It derives, via Latin <i>Eva</i>, from Hebrew <i>Havva</i>, which is considered to be a variant of the vocabulary word <i>hayya</i> ‘living’ or ‘animal’. Adam gave names to all the animals (Genesis 2:19–20) and then to his wife, who was ‘the mother of all living’ (Genesis 3:20)."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":6,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":15,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":60,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Basile Eve Culting was born in 1322, in Norf